<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-trigonometric-functions"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Trigonometric Functions</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We now construct sine and cosine from their power series. The basic
      algebraic identities will emerge from differentiation and from a simple
      uniqueness argument for the differential equation <m>y''+y=0</m>. This
      follows the same general strategy used in classical analysis texts such
      as Rosenlicht.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    For <m>x \in \R</m>, define
    <me>
      \sin x := \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}
      \qquad\text{and}\qquad
      \cos x := \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n x^{2n}}{(2n)!}.
    </me>
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-sine-cosine-series-convergence">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For every <m>R \gt 0</m>, the defining series for <m>\sin x</m> and
        <m>\cos x</m> converge uniformly on <m>[-R,R]</m>. In particular,
        <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> are continuous on <m>\R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        If <m>|x| \le R</m>, then
        <me>
          \left|\frac{(-1)^n x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}\right|
          \le
          \frac{R^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!},
          \qquad
          \left|\frac{(-1)^n x^{2n}}{(2n)!}\right|
          \le
          \frac{R^{2n}}{(2n)!}.
        </me>
        Both numerical majorants converge by the ratio test, so the
        Weierstrass M-test
        (<xref ref="thm-weierstrass-m-test-functions"/>) gives uniform
        convergence on <m>[-R,R]</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-sine-cosine-derivatives">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The functions <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> are analytic on <m>\R</m>,
        and
        <me>
          (\sin x)'=\cos x,
          \qquad
          (\cos x)'=-\sin x.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Each defining series has radius of convergence <m>\infty</m>, so
        <xref ref="thm-termwise-calculus-power-series"/> allows us to
        differentiate term by term:
        <me>
          (\sin x)'
          =
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n x^{2n}}{(2n)!}
          =
          \cos x,
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          (\cos x)'
          =
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n (2n)x^{2n-1}}{(2n)!}
          =
          -\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}
          =
          -\sin x.
        </me>
        Analyticity follows because both are power-series functions with
        infinite radius of convergence.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    The defining series immediately show that
    <me>
      \sin(-x)=-\sin x
      \qquad\text{and}\qquad
      \cos(-x)=\cos x,
    </me>
    so <m>\sin</m> is odd and <m>\cos</m> is even.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-pythagorean-identity">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For every <m>x \in \R</m>,
        <me>
          \sin^2 x+\cos^2 x=1.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>h(x)=\sin^2 x+\cos^2 x</m>. Using the product rule and
        <xref ref="prop-sine-cosine-derivatives"/>, we get
        <me>
          h'(x)=2\sin x \cos x + 2\cos x(-\sin x)=0.
        </me>
        By <xref ref="cor-derivative-zero-implies-constant"/>, <m>h</m> is
        constant on <m>\R</m>. Evaluating at <m>x=0</m> gives
        <me>
          h(0)=\sin^2 0+\cos^2 0=0^2+1^2=1.
        </me>
        Hence <m>h(x)=1</m> for all <m>x</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <lemma xml:id="lem-trig-ode-uniqueness">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>h \in C^2(\R)</m> satisfy
        <me>
          h''(x)=-h(x)
          \qquad \text{for all } x \in \R,
        </me>
        together with <m>h(0)=0</m> and <m>h'(0)=0</m>. Then
        <m>h(x)=0</m> for every <m>x \in \R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Consider the function
        <me>
          E(x)=h(x)^2+h'(x)^2.
        </me>
        Differentiating gives
        <me>
          E'(x)=2h(x)h'(x)+2h'(x)h''(x)
          =
          2h'(x)\bigl(h(x)+h''(x)\bigr)
          =0.
        </me>
        Hence <m>E</m> is constant by
        <xref ref="cor-derivative-zero-implies-constant"/>. Since
        <m>E(0)=h(0)^2+h'(0)^2=0</m>, we have <m>E(x)=0</m> for every
        <m>x</m>. Therefore both <m>h(x)</m> and <m>h'(x)</m> are identically
        zero.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </lemma>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-sine-cosine-addition-formulas">
    <title>Addition Formulas</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For all <m>x,a \in \R</m>,
        <me>
          \sin(x+a)=\sin x \cos a+\cos x \sin a,
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \cos(x+a)=\cos x \cos a-\sin x \sin a.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Fix <m>a \in \R</m>. Define
        <me>
          F(x)=\sin(x+a)
          \qquad\text{and}\qquad
          G(x)=\sin x \cos a+\cos x \sin a.
        </me>
        By <xref ref="prop-sine-cosine-derivatives"/>, both functions belong
        to <m>C^2(\R)</m> and satisfy <m>y''=-y</m>. Also,
        <me>
          F(0)=\sin a=G(0)
          \qquad\text{and}\qquad
          F'(0)=\cos a=G'(0).
        </me>
        Therefore <m>H=F-G</m> satisfies the hypotheses of
        <xref ref="lem-trig-ode-uniqueness"/>, so <m>H=0</m>. This proves the
        sine addition formula.
      </p>

      <p>
        For cosine, define
        <me>
          \widetilde{F}(x)=\cos(x+a)
          \qquad\text{and}\qquad
          \widetilde{G}(x)=\cos x \cos a-\sin x \sin a.
        </me>
        Again both satisfy <m>y''=-y</m>, and
        <me>
          \widetilde{F}(0)=\cos a=\widetilde{G}(0),
          \qquad
          \widetilde{F}'(0)=-\sin a=\widetilde{G}'(0).
        </me>
        Hence <m>\widetilde{F}=\widetilde{G}</m> by the same lemma.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-sine-positive-on-zero-two">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>0 \lt x \le 2</m>, then
        <me>
          0 \lt \sin x \le x.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        For <m>0 \lt x \le 2</m>, the successive term magnitudes in the sine
        series satisfy
        <me>
          \frac{x^{2n+3}/(2n+3)!}{x^{2n+1}/(2n+1)!}
          =
          \frac{x^2}{(2n+2)(2n+3)}
          \le
          \frac{4}{6}
          \lt
          1.
        </me>
        Thus the terms decrease in absolute value to <m>0</m>, so the
        alternating-series test gives
        <me>
          0 \lt \sin x \le x.
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-pi-over-two">
    <statement>
      <p>
        There exists a unique number <m>\pi/2 \in (1,2)</m> such that
        <me>
          \cos(\pi/2)=0.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        By <xref ref="prop-sine-cosine-derivatives"/> and
        <xref ref="prop-sine-positive-on-zero-two"/>, we have
        <me>
          (\cos x)'=-\sin x \lt 0
          \qquad \text{for } 0 \lt x \le 2.
        </me>
        Hence <m>\cos x</m> is strictly decreasing on <m>[0,2]</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Using the alternating-series estimate,
        <me>
          \cos 1
          =
          1-\frac{1}{2!}+\frac{1}{4!}-\cdots
          \gt
          1-\frac12
          \gt
          0,
        </me>
        while
        <me>
          \cos 2
          =
          1-\frac{2^2}{2!}+\frac{2^4}{4!}-\frac{2^6}{6!}+\cdots
          \lt
          1-2+\frac{16}{24}
          =
          -\frac13
          \lt
          0.
        </me>
        Therefore the Intermediate Value Theorem gives a zero of
        <m>\cos x</m> in <m>(1,2)</m>, and strict decrease makes that zero
        unique.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    We define <m>\pi</m><idx>\pi</idx> to be twice this number:
    <me>
      \pi := 2(\pi/2).
    </me>
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-trig-quarter-turn-periodicity">
    <title>Quarter-Turn Identities and Periodicity</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For every <m>x \in \R</m>,
        <me>
          \sin\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=\cos x,
          \qquad
          \cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=-\sin x,
        </me>
        and consequently
        <me>
          \sin(x+\pi)=-\sin x,
          \qquad
          \cos(x+\pi)=-\cos x,
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \sin(x+2\pi)=\sin x,
          \qquad
          \cos(x+2\pi)=\cos x.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        In particular,
        <me>
          \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=1,
          \qquad
          \sin(\pi)=0,
          \qquad
          \cos(\pi)=-1.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>\cos(\pi/2)=0</m> and <m>\sin^2(\pi/2)+\cos^2(\pi/2)=1</m>,
        we have <m>\sin(\pi/2)=1</m>. The addition formulas with
        <m>a=\pi/2</m> therefore give
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
            \sin\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
            &amp;=
            \sin x \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
            +
            \cos x \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\\
            &amp;=
            \cos x,
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
            \cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
            &amp;=
            \cos x \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
            -
            \sin x \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\\
            &amp;=
            -\sin x.
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Putting <m>x=\pi/2</m> into the first identity gives <m>\sin(\pi)=0</m>,
        and then the second identity yields <m>\cos(\pi)=-1</m>. Applying the
        addition formulas with <m>a=\pi</m> gives
        <me>
          \sin(x+\pi)=\sin x \cos \pi+\cos x \sin \pi=-\sin x,
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \cos(x+\pi)=\cos x \cos \pi-\sin x \sin \pi=-\cos x.
        </me>
        Replacing <m>x</m> by <m>x+\pi</m> in these formulas shows that
        <me>
          \sin(x+2\pi)=\sin x,
          \qquad
          \cos(x+2\pi)=\cos x.
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-sine-basic-limits">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For every <m>x \in \R</m>,
        <me>
          |\sin x| \le |x|,
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\sin x}{x}=1,
          \qquad
          \lim_{x\to 0} \cos x=1.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        By <xref ref="prop-pythagorean-identity"/>, we have
        <m>|\cos x| \le 1</m> for all <m>x</m>. Applying the Mean Value
        Theorem to <m>\sin</m> on the interval between <m>0</m> and <m>x</m>,
        we obtain
        <me>
          |\sin x-\sin 0| = |\cos c|\,|x|
        </me>
        for some <m>c</m> between <m>0</m> and <m>x</m>. Since
        <m>\sin 0=0</m>, it follows that <m>|\sin x| \le |x|</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Dividing the power series for <m>\sin x</m> by <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          \frac{\sin x}{x}
          =
          1-\frac{x^2}{3!}+\frac{x^4}{5!}-\cdots
          \qquad (x \neq 0).
        </me>
        The right-hand side converges to <m>1</m> as <m>x \to 0</m>, and the
        power series for <m>\cos x</m> plainly tends to <m>1</m> as well.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>
</section>
